<TITLE> Europe shares fall on renewed US recession fears </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Paris, Jan 28 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - European stocks fell in early trade on Monday as renewed fears over the prospect of a US recession knocked down equity markets worldwide, while concerns over more mortgage-related writedowns hit banking shares. At 0813 GMT, the FTSEurofirst 300 index of top European shares was down 1.7 percent at 1,307.75 points. The index has fallen 13 percent so far in 2008. Banking shares took a beating, with the DJ Stoxx bank index down 1.9 percent. Societe Generale was down 3.5 percent, and UBS down 1.7 percent. Fortis moved in the oposite direction, jumping 7 percent. The Belgian-Dutch bank said on Sunday its 2007 profit could be hit by 1 billion euros ($1.47 billion), depending on the valuation models it will choose to assess the value of its subprime portfolio. The stock had dropped sharply on Friday on market talk of a profit warning. Shares in Asia slid, with Japan down around 4 percent and Hong Kong down more than 6 percent on concerns over the outlook ofr the U.S. economy.
